2 Data

This is data extracted for 87 studies, with 595 effect sizes. In addition, there are 13 other studies that report data for (generalized) linear mixed models, but I am unsure how comparable they are.

The data includes raw effect sizes (Fishers z transformed correlation coefficients) for the relationship between a variety of response variables (species richness, abundance, occurrence, genetic differentiation and a few others), and metrics of connectivity categorized into different types following their definitions (as described by (Kindlmann and Burel 2008), (Kupfer 2012), and (Keeley, Beier, and Jenness 2021).

The following figures show the distribution of effect sizes across different categories of the data.

For the first density plot, the dashed lines are the mean effects. All the plots are grouped by the study taxa, and the raw correlation coefficients were transformed into the Fishers z scale.

3 Journal and study information

4 Taxonomic information

Note that the taxonomic information is not complete for all studies, and the taxonomic resolution varies between studies; e.g.studies with arthropoda, and many studies with plantae as focal taxa are only reported at a broad taxonomic level.

5 Connectivity metrics

Connectivity metrics were binned based on their type (structural, potential, functional) and the feature of the landscape that connectivity is being assessed for, based on authors descriptions of the metric and definitions from (Keeley, Beier, and Jenness 2021) and Fragstats documentation. The following figures show the distribution of effect sizes across these categories.

The most common connectivity metrics were based on habitat area in a buffer (typically based on dispersal distances), or euclidean distances between sites/patches. Because of the large spectrum of metrics used, it is likely that the categories these metrics are binned into (the two previous figures) will be used as moderators in the meta-analysis.

6 Response metrics

Many papers report multiple response metrics, particularly for species richness and abundance or occurrence and abundance. Genetic studies often only report one response metric related to connectivity; genetic differentiation (a.k.a. genetic distance), but these are sometimes based on different genetic markers (e.g.microsatellites, SNPs, etc.).

One major question for the meta-analysis: How to handle multiple response metrics?

  • Everything into a global model with to get an overall effect of connectivity on biodiversity outcomes with and without moderators coded for metric type and response type.
  • Seperate meta-analyses for each of the response metrics. Since each of these response metrics capture different aspects of biodiversity, it is likely that the mechanisms of how connectivity impacts them isnt the same.

In addition, the reponse of the connectivity metrics on biodiversity were assessed using different correlation types, including Pearsons correlation, Spearmans correlation, and partial-correlation. The following figure shows the distribution of effect sizes across these correlation types. Note though that data was extracted prioritizing Pearsons correlation coefficients, Spearmans correlation, and raw site-level data where available. Partial-correlation coefficients were extracted when available, but these are less common.

7 Next steps:

  • Finish extracting relevant information for the rest of eligible papers.
  • Write a script for conducting a global meta-analysis for all effect sizes.
  • Finish writing script for conducting analysis meta-regression per connectivity metric and biodiversity metric that have a large enough sample size.
  • Estimate variance-covariance matrix for multiple effect sizes that come from the same study, for dependent effect sizes. Incorporate into the model and evaluate the impact of this on the results.
